Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pour the @water{500%ml} into a large #saucepan{} 
and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Add the @vegetable stock powder{1} 
and stir to dissolve. Tip the @quinoa{120%g} into a #sieve{} and rinse with cold 
water.

Remove the stalk top from the @aubergine{1}, halve lengthways and chop into 
wedges about the length and width of your index finger. Place on a lined 
#baking tray{} in a single layer. In a #small bowl{}, mix the @ground coriander{1%tsp} 
with the @olive oil{2%tbsp} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Drizzle this 
over the aubergine, make sure it gets a good coating. Roast on the middle of 
your oven until crispy, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, add the quinoa to the boiling stock, stir and reduce the heat to 
medium. Bubble away until the seeds have split, the quinoa has tripled in 
volume and is tender enough to eat, ~{15%minutes}. When cooked, drain in the 
sieve, pop back into your pan and cover with a lid to keep warm.

Halve the @cherry plum tomatoes{200%g} and put in a #bowl{}. Finely chop the 
@flat leaf parsley{10%g}(finely chopped, stalks and all). Pierce the bag the 
@hazelnuts{25%g} are in, then bash them in their bag with the bottom of a 
#frying pan{} or #rolling pin{} until lightly crushed. Add the parsley and 
hazelnuts to the tomatoes along with the @balsamic vinegar{1} and 
@olive oil{1%tbsp}. Add a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} and mix together. 
Keep to one side.

Cut the @halloumi{250%g} into four slices per person. Heat a drizzle of oil in 
a frying pan on medium-high heat. Once hot, lay in the halloumi slices and 
cook until golden, ~{3-4%minutes} on each side. Then remove from the pan and 
set aside.

Serve the quinoa in #bowls{} and top with the roasted aubergine and half the 
tomato salsa. Place the halloumi slices on top and spoon over the remaining 
salsa. Enjoy!